WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:15.060
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. In today's&nbsp;
video, we're going to move towards reconsidering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:15.060 --> 00:00:21.330
natural numbers, which are, of course, a very&nbsp;
fundamental part of mathematics. It's actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:21.330 --> 00:00:28.290
how we started this series some years ago. But&nbsp;
now, with our investigation of really big numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.290 --> 00:00:33.450
and the really big arithmetic that goes with&nbsp;
those big numbers, we've started to see that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.450 --> 00:00:39.780
maybe there's room for reconsideration&nbsp;
of what a natural number actually is.

00:00:39.780 --> 00:00:42.450
So, here are some questions that will motivate us:

00:00:43.320 --> 00:00:50.430
What exactly is a natural number? Can we&nbsp;
say precisely, concretely, and logically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:50.430 --> 00:00:55.020
what a natural number is?
Should we distinguish between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:55.020 --> 00:01:05.370
different types of natural numbers? Maybe there's&nbsp;
some reason for separating the different kinds&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:05.370 --> 00:01:10.020
of things that we've been currently grouping&nbsp;
together into one big box into separate boxes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:10.020 --> 00:01:17.880
and looking at things a little bit more finely.
Should we distinguish between natural numbers and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.880 --> 00:01:27.180
arithmetic expressions? Arithmetic expressions&nbsp;
can evaluate to numbers, but there's some reason&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.180 --> 00:01:33.450
to believe that we should treat them as something&nbsp;
separate from the numbers that they evaluate to.&nbsp;

00:01:36.060 --> 00:01:42.000
In thinking about these questions, I think it's&nbsp;
instructive to keep in mind the words of a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:49.770
well-known American mathematician, Errett&nbsp;
Bishop (1928-1983), who was a pioneer in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:49.770 --> 00:01:55.980
what is sometimes called constructive mathematics.&nbsp;
We're going to be talking about his work,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.980 --> 00:02:01.980
especially when we get to calculus and analysis&nbsp;
more. He was a very important thinker in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.980 --> 00:02:07.290
20th century, one who realized that the&nbsp;
status quo really needed to be moved in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.290 --> 00:02:14.930
different direction. But he gave a very lovely&nbsp;
prescription here, which I think is well worth&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.930 --> 00:02:22.430
studying. He says, "Meaningful distinctions need&nbsp;
to be preserved." Meaningful distinctions need&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:22.430 --> 00:02:26.480
to be preserved. He's talking about a situation&nbsp;
where you're looking at something and there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:26.480 --> 00:02:29.810
different kinds of objects, and there's&nbsp;
something fundamentally different about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:29.810 --> 00:02:36.050
them. What you don't want to do is just lump them&nbsp;
together, ignoring those fundamental differences&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.050 --> 00:02:43.190
that are actually there. You want to acknowledge&nbsp;
those differences, those distinctions, and build&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:43.190 --> 00:02:50.240
them into your description of what's going on.&nbsp;
Very sensible and a very useful kind of dictum.

00:02:50.240 --> 00:02:57.500
So far in this course, we have treated natural&nbsp;
numbers as belonging to one type, a type called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:57.500 --> 00:03:04.040
nat. This has included actually quite a few&nbsp;
different kinds of objects. So we started out&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:04.040 --> 00:03:10.160
by thinking of a number as a rather primitive&nbsp;
listing of marks or strokes on a page, perhaps&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:16.790
going back to some kind of Neanderthal arithmetic.&nbsp;
Then we moved to Hindu-Arabic numbers like 54,107,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.630 --> 00:03:22.070
which, of course, is very different from&nbsp;
this—it’s a different kind of object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:22.070 --> 00:03:28.580
really. And then we considered more advanced&nbsp;
arithmetic expressions like 10 to the 300 or maybe&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.580 --> 00:03:34.370
this expression here, or maybe even something a&nbsp;
bit more sophisticated with a triangle operation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.370 --> 00:03:39.860
or something even more sophisticated with&nbsp;
one of these higher hyper-operations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:39.860 --> 00:03:46.010
or maybe even something like this, where&nbsp;
the hyper-operation is now indexed with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:46.010 --> 00:03:52.460
this n to the n plus 5n to the fifth plus 3,&nbsp;
something like this humongous, huge number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:52.460 --> 00:03:57.500
which we really have no control over but&nbsp;
nevertheless is something that we can write down.

00:03:57.500 --> 00:04:02.690
So this is a very wide range of&nbsp;
possibilities, isn't it? I mean,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:02.690 --> 00:04:06.590
we're starting with something really&nbsp;
primitive and moving to something which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.590 --> 00:04:14.570
is pretty sophisticated and really beyond our&nbsp;
capabilities of understanding in any solid,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.570 --> 00:04:22.340
meaningful way. And it's natural to think,&nbsp;
well, is this just too wide a net? And I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.340 --> 00:04:28.100
think we can acknowledge that casting&nbsp;
such a wide net does lead to problems.

00:04:28.100 --> 00:04:36.140
So one key problem is that most of our theorems&nbsp;
about numbers and their arithmetic start to break&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.140 --> 00:04:42.530
down and then fail as we move from small,&nbsp;
primitive numbers through to Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:42.530 --> 00:04:48.890
numbers and through to these mega-huge&nbsp;
mathematical arithmetic expressions for numbers.

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:56.840
So, in particular, here’s a very important&nbsp;
example related to primes and the fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:05.240
theorem of arithmetic. We all know that every&nbsp;
natural number can be factored as a product of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.240 --> 00:05:13.130
prime numbers in essentially a unique way—that's&nbsp;
the fundamental theorem of arithmetic. Now, even&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:13.130 --> 00:05:17.810
though that's been around for thousands of years&nbsp;
(it goes back to Euclid), it actually is a little&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:17.810 --> 00:05:25.010
bit problematic. In fact, it’s a lot problematic&nbsp;
once we start getting to bigger numbers. This is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:25.010 --> 00:05:35.270
curious and disconcerting aspect of the way things&nbsp;
are. Prime factorization is actually a technique&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.270 --> 00:05:41.240
that only really works for small numbers—and&nbsp;
"small numbers" is in quotes here—numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:41.240 --> 00:05:47.480
you know, that are roughly familiar to us in&nbsp;
our usual range of mathematical activities.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:54.260
A billion, a trillion, maybe a trillion&nbsp;
trillion—numbers like this in this range,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:54.260 --> 00:06:01.310
prime factorization is no problem. However, if&nbsp;
we go significantly beyond that range, into the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.310 --> 00:06:08.780
realms that we've been exploring in our last few&nbsp;
videos, then sadly, prime factorization weakens&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.780 --> 00:06:15.500
and ultimately breaks down completely. It weakens&nbsp;
and then ultimately it breaks down completely.

00:06:15.500 --> 00:06:25.460
For example, our favorite, Z = 10 triangle&nbsp;
10 + 23, almost surely has no well-defined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.460 --> 00:06:33.800
prime factorization. The fundamental theorem of&nbsp;
arithmetic does not actually work with this thing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.800 --> 00:06:40.150
So if we think of this as a number, then it's no&nbsp;
longer true that every number has a prime factor.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:40.150 --> 00:06:47.260
This thing doesn't. And I'm going to talk more&nbsp;
about this, but just to give you an initial idea:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.260 --> 00:06:56.080
So here is a picture of the number line from&nbsp;
0 or 1 up to Z. There it is up there, and say,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:56.080 --> 00:07:04.330
somewhere down here is 10 triangle 4. And this&nbsp;
is not exactly a linear scale, but this is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:04.330 --> 00:07:09.580
range that we've seen that's sort of accessible&nbsp;
to us in terms of being able to write things down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:09.580 --> 00:07:17.530
explicitly in our universe, even assuming we&nbsp;
can employ vast hard drives at Planck scales.

00:07:17.530 --> 00:07:26.050
Now, perhaps in God's garden, in some different&nbsp;
world where all of these numbers were visible—if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:26.050 --> 00:07:31.060
we can kind of imagine that for a second or try to&nbsp;
imagine that for a second—it's not entirely clear&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.060 --> 00:07:35.140
that that has any meaning, but let's just play&nbsp;
this game. So, we'll imagine that we have God's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.140 --> 00:07:43.240
garden, and in God's garden, we have all of these&nbsp;
numbers. And there, perhaps, this number Z does&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:48.700
have a prime factorization, and the prime factors&nbsp;
will—well, there’ll be lots of them, typically,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.700 --> 00:07:55.000
and so many of them will be in our range, these&nbsp;
ones down here. And we can find some of them. For&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:02.080
example, 3 is a prime factor of this thing. Okay?&nbsp;
So, there will be hundreds, perhaps thousands,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:02.080 --> 00:08:07.600
or perhaps trillions of factors that we actually&nbsp;
can find, but there will also be lots of factors&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.600 --> 00:08:15.610
which are bigger, which are beyond 10 triangle 4,&nbsp;
but still much smaller than this thing here. Okay?

00:08:15.610 --> 00:08:21.640
Now, when we look at this same factorization&nbsp;
in our world, okay? In our world, most of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:26.680
numbers here are lost to us. We cannot write&nbsp;
them down because they are too big to fit in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.680 --> 00:08:32.740
our universe, no matter what arithmetical&nbsp;
system we pick or choose. In particular,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:32.740 --> 00:08:37.750
most of these primes that are appearing here&nbsp;
in this ideal factorization are not going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.750 --> 00:08:43.720
be visible to us anymore—they're completely&nbsp;
inaccessible. So even though this number—yes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:43.720 --> 00:08:49.900
we can write it down, it only takes a little bit&nbsp;
of room—now, primes involved in factoring it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.900 --> 00:08:54.760
most of them are going to be completely&nbsp;
beyond us. This is very disconcerting,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.760 --> 00:09:00.550
right? But it's a necessary consequence of&nbsp;
the realization that the complexity of most&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.550 --> 00:09:06.730
of these numbers less than Z is overwhelming&nbsp;
from our point of view. We've seen that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:06.730 --> 00:09:09.790
right? That's what we established a&nbsp;
few videos ago when we were talking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.790 --> 00:09:15.430
about that. That's a consequence of this. A&nbsp;
consequence is that prime factorization of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:15.430 --> 00:09:21.700
something like Z is completely problematic.&nbsp;
It doesn't really exist in a meaningful way.

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:27.340
Here’s a related important example of&nbsp;
something that becomes problematic:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:27.910 --> 00:09:34.270
this is Euclid's theorem about an unbounded number&nbsp;
of primes. So, Euclid proved the fact that if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:34.270 --> 00:09:41.770
have a finite number of primes, you can always&nbsp;
find another prime which is outside that given&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:41.770 --> 00:09:47.590
collection of primes—sort of telling us that&nbsp;
the primes are unbounded, that we can always&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:47.590 --> 00:09:54.220
find another one no matter how many we have.&nbsp;
Now, this is often taken in modern times to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:54.220 --> 00:09:58.780
essentially equivalent to the statement that there&nbsp;
are an infinite number of primes. Okay? So, it is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:58.780 --> 00:10:04.300
commonly asserted in 20th-century mathematics&nbsp;
that there are an infinite number of primes.

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:12.460
People, this is rubbish, okay? It’s nonsense. It's&nbsp;
completely untrue. And the reason it's completely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.460 --> 00:10:19.210
untrue is very simple: It's because there are&nbsp;
not an infinite number of any things. We are not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:19.210 --> 00:10:23.950
living in an infinite world. There's nothing&nbsp;
about our world which is infinite—at least,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:23.950 --> 00:10:27.820
there's no evidence to suggest that there's&nbsp;
anything about our world which is infinite in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:27.820 --> 00:10:32.080
any aspect whatsoever. There are&nbsp;
not an infinite number of frogs;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:35.980
there are not an infinite number of electrons;&nbsp;
there are not an infinite number of ideas;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:35.980 --> 00:10:39.370
there are not an infinite number of theorems;&nbsp;
there are not an infinite number of people;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:39.370 --> 00:10:44.110
there are not an infinite number of ghosts;&nbsp;
there are not an infinite number of anything,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:44.110 --> 00:10:55.720
including prime numbers. We can see that when we&nbsp;
start to explore these bigger numbers, all right?

00:10:55.720 --> 00:11:01.000
So, if we never go beyond sort of the comfort&nbsp;
zone, then we can kind of imagine that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:05.950
fairy tale idea that we have just keeps on going&nbsp;
in some kind of uniform way. But we've seen that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:05.950 --> 00:11:10.870
that's very far from being the case, that we&nbsp;
actually have a completely different experience&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:10.870 --> 00:11:17.260
of numbers and their arithmetic once we start&nbsp;
seriously exploring bigger numbers. And what we've&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:22.930
seen is that the numbers that we have control of&nbsp;
become fewer and fewer and sparser and sparser,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:22.930 --> 00:11:29.770
and they start to thin out and become ever more&nbsp;
bizarre. And then, ultimately, beyond that point,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:29.770 --> 00:11:36.400
there’s a point where things drizzle out and&nbsp;
stop altogether. And we can't say precisely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:36.400 --> 00:11:43.210
when that happens or where it happens, but happen&nbsp;
it will because of the limited nature of the world&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:43.210 --> 00:11:49.870
in which we live. It's just a consequence&nbsp;
of facing the reality that the physicists,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:49.870 --> 00:11:55.510
the astronomers, the cosmologists&nbsp;
are telling us that we inhabit.

00:11:55.510 --> 00:12:06.820
So, in fact, I claim that to be very precise,&nbsp;
there are no primes bigger than Z = 10 triangle&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:06.820 --> 00:12:15.430
10 + 23. There are no primes bigger than this&nbsp;
number. It's not just that there are bigger&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:15.430 --> 00:12:20.890
primes, but we can't find them—no, I assert that&nbsp;
it's actually the case that there are no primes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:20.890 --> 00:12:27.190
bigger than this thing. There are just no numbers&nbsp;
that can be expressible in our universe which have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:27.190 --> 00:12:40.360
the property that they are bigger than this and&nbsp;
are also prime. This is a disconcerting statement,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:40.360 --> 00:12:45.670
of course, and you may say, well, it's just&nbsp;
a matter of time before our computers get big&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:45.670 --> 00:12:50.680
enough and we'll be able to explore these regions&nbsp;
and find primes—no, okay? You're not gonna find&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:50.680 --> 00:12:55.720
a prime bigger than this. Future viewers, am&nbsp;
I right? Maybe viewers from a thousand years&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:55.720 --> 00:13:02.140
from now, I'm willing to bet that you have not&nbsp;
found any primes bigger than this number. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:07.030
probably it's more evident to you that I'm&nbsp;
right—there are no big primes of this kind.

00:13:07.030 --> 00:13:15.670
So, what about Euclid's proof? So, Euclid's&nbsp;
proof asserts that no matter how many finite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:15.670 --> 00:13:20.290
primes you have, you can always find a bigger&nbsp;
one. Well, it turns out—and we'll have to have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:20.290 --> 00:13:25.960
a look at this—that Euclid's proof contains a&nbsp;
subtle logical error. It's not a correct proof,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:25.960 --> 00:13:31.060
in fact, okay? If we look closely at it, not&nbsp;
just kind of quickly look at it, but actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:31.060 --> 00:13:37.210
look very carefully at what the proof is telling&nbsp;
us and what it's telling us to do, we see that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:37.210 --> 00:13:44.230
there are some subtle assumptions built in that,&nbsp;
upon closer examination, aren't supportable. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:44.230 --> 00:13:49.990
the proof is not, in fact, correct. The&nbsp;
proof is correct for smaller numbers—yes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:49.990 --> 00:13:56.020
I'll buy that. But eventually, the&nbsp;
proof reaches a stage, some bound,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:56.020 --> 00:14:01.600
where the arguments no longer apply, and the proof&nbsp;
breaks down. And in fact, the theorem is no longer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:01.600 --> 00:14:08.380
a theorem—it’s just plainly false. There are no&nbsp;
prime numbers bigger than 10 triangle 10 + 23.

00:14:08.380 --> 00:14:15.880
But it's not just results that go back to Euclid&nbsp;
that are problematic—many modern so-called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:22.690
theorems in number theory are simply incorrect&nbsp;
as currently stated. They are simply not true,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:22.690 --> 00:14:31.150
and they rely on a false understanding of the&nbsp;
nature of the natural numbers. There really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:31.150 --> 00:14:37.960
is a serious misconception floating around that&nbsp;
basically pervades all of modern number theory.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:37.960 --> 00:14:46.180
All right? So almost all of these fancy modern&nbsp;
theorems are, in fact, limited in extent. They&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:46.180 --> 00:14:52.090
need to be recast in a more limited, careful&nbsp;
way. The bounds of possible applicability of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:52.090 --> 00:15:00.220
these theorems need to be investigated, okay?&nbsp;
Blanket statements are fraught with difficulty.

00:15:00.220 --> 00:15:06.400
So, another serious problem is induction,&nbsp;
where we try to prove things by this process&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:12.580
of starting with one and then proving things&nbsp;
one at a time. So, this whole enterprise becomes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:17.650
problematic if we can't actually get to the&nbsp;
numbers that we're interested in, say like Z,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:17.650 --> 00:15:24.580
by counting from 1 to Z one step at a time.&nbsp;
Clearly, if your proof that something is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:24.580 --> 00:15:31.510
true for Z involves starting with 1 and then&nbsp;
proceeding one step at a time, from 1 to 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:32.430 --> 00:15:35.850
from 2 to 3, from 3 to 4, and then you keep&nbsp;
going until you finally get to Z—if that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:35.850 --> 00:15:42.600
your proof technique, and then you find out that,&nbsp;
in fact, wait a minute, most of the numbers that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:42.600 --> 00:15:49.740
we encounter between 1 and Z are, in fact, not&nbsp;
actually reachable. We can't actually get to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:49.740 --> 00:15:54.870
them because they're so vast they don't fit into&nbsp;
the universe. Then that clearly breaks down the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:54.870 --> 00:16:00.360
logical argument, right? That we no longer&nbsp;
have proven our fact for Z; we've proven it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:00.360 --> 00:16:04.980
only to the extent that we've been able to go&nbsp;
from 1 to whatever number we're considering,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:04.980 --> 00:16:12.660
one step at a time. It's a logical necessity&nbsp;
that if you're only gonna go one step at a time,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:12.660 --> 00:16:16.740
you can only make statements about things that&nbsp;
you can get to by going one step at a time.

00:16:16.740 --> 00:16:28.860
So, we need to reconsider a lot of things&nbsp;
in number theory. We need to think much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:28.860 --> 00:16:36.270
more carefully and clearly. We need to take into&nbsp;
consideration the real dichotomy between small,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:36.270 --> 00:16:43.080
comfortable, familiar arithmetic and this&nbsp;
much more problematic, almost inaccessible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:48.810
arithmetic that we eventually get to when we&nbsp;
start to explore far outside our comfort zone.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:48.810 --> 00:16:57.120
And one way to start to try to make things more&nbsp;
precise and to nail things down more clearly is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:57.120 --> 00:17:03.090
to go back to the very fundamental questions&nbsp;
that we started this video with, which is:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:03.090 --> 00:17:09.360
What is exactly a natural number? This is at the&nbsp;
heart of the matter—what is a natural number?

00:17:09.360 --> 00:17:18.780
Well, we have at least three identifiable,&nbsp;
different ways of looking at natural numbers. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:22.260
our first tier is really the one&nbsp;
that we started this series with,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:22.260 --> 00:17:30.930
where we were thinking about natural numbers in&nbsp;
a very primitive fashion—basically as a sequence&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.930 --> 00:17:39.120
of strokes or marks on a page. And that's&nbsp;
sufficient for us to define an arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:39.120 --> 00:17:45.030
involving addition and multiplication in a&nbsp;
relatively simple, kind of naive way. We,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:45.030 --> 00:17:50.130
in fact, don't actually even need to have names&nbsp;
for such things. We could say this is mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:50.130 --> 00:17:57.240
mark, mark plus mark, mark, mark, mark equals&nbsp;
mark, mark, mark, mark, mark, mark, mark, mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:57.240 --> 00:18:03.960
mark. And a little bit of a departure from what&nbsp;
I did in that very first video is that now I'm&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:03.960 --> 00:18:10.830
putting these collections of strokes or marks&nbsp;
in little boxes because we're familiar with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:10.830 --> 00:18:16.650
multisets. So, we're using a multiset kind&nbsp;
of idea here—this is a multiset of marks,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:16.650 --> 00:18:24.390
okay? And that sort of makes things a little bit&nbsp;
tighter. And of course, we can then sort of recast&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:24.390 --> 00:18:31.440
this in terms of our familiar Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
formulation—this is really 7 + 4 = 11,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:32.130 --> 00:18:37.200
this is really 3 times 4 = 12. But then we can&nbsp;
sort of represent this as just being a shorthand&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:37.200 --> 00:18:49.980
for this more fundamental manifestation&nbsp;
of the arithmetic of natural numbers.

00:18:49.980 --> 00:18:57.690
So, with this view, a natural number is really,&nbsp;
well, it's a bunch of strokes or marks on a page,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:57.690 --> 00:19:03.870
perhaps enclosed in some kind of box or&nbsp;
container or multiset. And then another&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:03.870 --> 00:19:09.750
big step up is to go to the Hindu-Arabic natural&nbsp;
number presentation that we're familiar with,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:09.750 --> 00:19:16.620
that we actually use in everyday life, where&nbsp;
numbers now are things like 34 or 152. And the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:16.620 --> 00:19:22.530
arithmetic is done at this level, where that&nbsp;
we learn in primary school: 34 + 152 = 186,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.530 --> 00:19:30.060
57 times 14 = 798, and so on. And although there's&nbsp;
no natural connection between these two things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:30.060 --> 00:19:36.090
there's also a natural separation. And there&nbsp;
are some senses in which this is a more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:36.090 --> 00:19:43.440
sophisticated and more wide-ranging&nbsp;
approach to numbers than this one.

00:19:43.440 --> 00:19:52.320
And then another big step is to consider&nbsp;
just arithmetic expressions. So, for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:52.320 --> 00:19:58.710
we could say, look at this number here, 3 to the&nbsp;
fifth minus 14 squared. And that's an arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:58.710 --> 00:20:04.110
expression for a number. Here's another arithmetic&nbsp;
expression: 6 factorial. And here's another&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:04.110 --> 00:20:11.910
arithmetic expression: 13 times 59. Okay? So&nbsp;
here, we're working with some kind of arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:11.910 --> 00:20:17.430
expressions, and we can do arithmetic with these&nbsp;
arithmetic expressions as evidenced here. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:17.430 --> 00:20:22.530
you can see that this is going to be much more&nbsp;
challenging to set up because we have to decide,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:22.530 --> 00:20:27.990
well, what kinds of expressions we're going to&nbsp;
allow, what are the rules that we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:27.990 --> 00:20:32.280
adopt, when are we going to decide when&nbsp;
two expressions are equal, and so on.

00:20:32.280 --> 00:20:38.670
So although we could, and perhaps we should,&nbsp;
talk about this, it might be useful for us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:38.670 --> 00:20:42.900
to really separate what we currently have.&nbsp;
So currently, we jumble all these together,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:42.900 --> 00:20:47.370
and we say, "I'll consider this number here,&nbsp;
that's 4, and consider this number 798,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:47.370 --> 00:20:52.860
and consider this number 13 times 59." We&nbsp;
treat them all as more or less just different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:52.860 --> 00:20:58.110
manifestations of the same thing. But what I'm&nbsp;
saying here is that what we've been talking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:58.110 --> 00:21:04.440
about really leads us to want to separate things&nbsp;
into different levels so that there are different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:04.440 --> 00:21:14.670
kinds of natural numbers. And we might actually&nbsp;
introduce different types for what currently is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:14.670 --> 00:21:23.850
just only one type. So, we could say reserve nat&nbsp;
to be a primitive natural number of this kind,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:23.850 --> 00:21:32.670
and we could use num to represent Hindu-Arabic&nbsp;
natural numbers, and we could introduce something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:32.670 --> 00:21:40.080
like num expression or num X to denote some kind&nbsp;
of arithmetic expression, although we would have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:40.080 --> 00:21:48.390
to be more precise about the nature of this kind&nbsp;
of object. So this way, we would have different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:48.390 --> 00:21:54.750
levels of natural numbers and not just the single,&nbsp;
all-embracing container that we currently have.

00:21:54.750 --> 00:22:01.890
So, let’s say a little bit about that first&nbsp;
type, the primitive natural numbers. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:01.890 --> 00:22:08.850
note that we are going to use M-sets or multisets&nbsp;
as containers for that, so that we really are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:08.850 --> 00:22:14.410
adopting this data structure point of view here.&nbsp;
And this is another example of the very useful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:14.410 --> 00:22:23.830
application of multisets: that they give us a&nbsp;
vehicle for introducing and creating, in fact,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:23.830 --> 00:22:29.530
the natural numbers, okay? So, this is very&nbsp;
different from the set-theoretical formulation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:29.530 --> 00:22:36.490
as we described a few videos ago, attributing it&nbsp;
to John von Neumann—the idea that a natural number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:36.490 --> 00:22:44.710
is a set, a set of sets, and everything is built&nbsp;
up from the empty set in terms of sets of empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:44.710 --> 00:22:50.440
sets and other sets, and so on, nested inside&nbsp;
each other in a rather complicated way. So here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:50.440 --> 00:22:56.320
the possibility is that we can simplify things&nbsp;
dramatically because we can use the M-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:56.320 --> 00:23:02.080
notation. Then we only have these single primitive&nbsp;
objects, which we might call a stroke or a mark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:02.080 --> 00:23:07.270
which then go on to populate our M-sets&nbsp;
and create our natural numbers for us.

00:23:07.270 --> 00:23:18.700
So here then is a definition, okay? A definition&nbsp;
of what a natural number is—actually, more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:18.700 --> 00:23:23.800
precisely, what a primitive natural number is,&nbsp;
if we want to be a little bit more specific. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:23.800 --> 00:23:32.920
a primitive natural number is an M-set of marks.&nbsp;
This is what we can call a mark: an M-set of marks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:32.920 --> 00:23:40.570
is a natural number, and this type nat is going&nbsp;
to be now our type that represents a primitive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:40.570 --> 00:23:49.330
natural number. So, an M-set of marks is specified&nbsp;
by writing it down clearly and completely. There's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:49.330 --> 00:23:55.120
now only one way of really officially&nbsp;
writing down a primitive natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:55.120 --> 00:24:03.310
which is to write it out like this—it's an M-set&nbsp;
of marks. So, you have to make all the marks,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:03.310 --> 00:24:09.340
and you put them in a square bracket box, and&nbsp;
that is a natural number. That more precisely is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:09.340 --> 00:24:16.240
a primitive natural number, an element of nat. So&nbsp;
note that this is similar but somewhat different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:16.240 --> 00:24:22.720
from our very first lecture, MF1, in that&nbsp;
lecture we hadn't talked about data structures,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:22.720 --> 00:24:30.570
we didn't have the idea of sets or lists or&nbsp;
ordered sets or multisets, and we didn't put our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:30.570 --> 00:24:38.400
strings of marks or strokes in a box or container.&nbsp;
But now that we are familiar with multisets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:38.400 --> 00:24:43.470
and we are a little bit comfortable with them, and&nbsp;
we recognize that they're flexible objects, we are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:43.470 --> 00:24:47.130
gonna do that. So, we're going to shift gears&nbsp;
just a little bit—we're allowed to do that—and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:47.130 --> 00:24:55.380
we're going to now regard a natural number as&nbsp;
an M-set of marks in the usual M-set notation.

00:24:55.380 --> 00:25:01.740
So, M-sets, of course, I remind you, allow&nbsp;
repetition—we definitely need that because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:01.740 --> 00:25:07.650
there's only one type of thing that's happening&nbsp;
in here—and there's no commas because the order&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:07.650 --> 00:25:13.350
doesn't matter. You can interchange the order and&nbsp;
it doesn't matter—it doesn’t change things. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:13.350 --> 00:25:23.220
so this is really a fundamentally new but&nbsp;
simple approach to a really fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:23.220 --> 00:25:27.780
object in mathematics: the natural numbers, and&nbsp;
how we're going to think about natural numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:27.780 --> 00:25:33.810
okay? And it's well worth pondering about the&nbsp;
pros and cons of this proposed definition.

00:25:33.810 --> 00:25:39.540
So, let me reiterate that again because it's&nbsp;
rather important. So, in Math Foundations 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:39.540 --> 00:25:45.570
we did define a natural number as a string of&nbsp;
ones, and we expressed this natural number as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:45.570 --> 00:25:52.800
1 1 1 1. So, we considered the stroke as being&nbsp;
1, okay? So here, we're departing from that. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:52.800 --> 00:25:58.620
our basic object is this stroke or mark, which&nbsp;
is not to be identified with the number 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:58.620 --> 00:26:05.670
which is rather this. So, the number 1 is&nbsp;
the M-set consisting of a single mark. Here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:05.670 --> 00:26:10.080
I've written it again, okay? So,&nbsp;
this mark here is not the number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:10.080 --> 00:26:21.660
1. The number 1 is now the M-set consisting&nbsp;
of that single mark—that’s the number 1. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:21.660 --> 00:26:25.890
this is a departure from what we did before,&nbsp;
utilizing our familiarity with M-sets.

00:26:25.890 --> 00:26:34.290
There are some clear advantages in making our&nbsp;
natural numbers as multisets of these strokes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:34.290 --> 00:26:39.650
or marks. So, in particular, the boundaries&nbsp;
are clear, so there's less ambiguity or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:39.650 --> 00:26:45.260
possible confusion when we have lots of different&nbsp;
natural numbers sort of on the same page or on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:45.260 --> 00:26:50.480
same line. If we don't have the boundaries, then&nbsp;
there's more likelihood that these things will run&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:50.480 --> 00:26:55.400
together, especially if we're wanting to juxtapose&nbsp;
them or get them close to each other. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:55.400 --> 00:27:02.690
in particular, for multiplying M-sets, say like&nbsp;
this, then it's completely clear what we're doing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:02.690 --> 00:27:08.000
and we can get rid of the multiplication&nbsp;
sign and just juxtapose the two M-sets. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:12.410
that's now possible. But if you didn't have&nbsp;
M-sets there, then this would be a rather&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:12.410 --> 00:27:17.600
dangerous thing to do because it’s easy to&nbsp;
confuse this one with what we would call 7.

00:27:17.600 --> 00:27:24.560
And there's another interesting consequence of&nbsp;
working with M-sets because we've seen from our&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:24.560 --> 00:27:31.340
experience that in the world of M-sets, there is&nbsp;
a distinguished M-set, which is the empty M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:31.340 --> 00:27:41.630
okay? So, this empty M-set, which we denote&nbsp;
like this, is both natural and useful. And so,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:41.630 --> 00:27:49.610
if we're going to define a primitive natural&nbsp;
number as an M-set of marks, then it follows&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:49.610 --> 00:27:58.340
that we should allow the possibility of&nbsp;
having an empty M-set of marks. And so,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:58.340 --> 00:28:06.110
that means that what we usually think of as zero&nbsp;
naturally plays a role here. It naturally arises&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:06.110 --> 00:28:13.940
as a type of natural number, which is, of course,&nbsp;
different from the historical story. And it's also&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:13.940 --> 00:28:20.420
different from what we did in the first part&nbsp;
of this series—we have up till now not treated&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:20.420 --> 00:28:24.980
zero as a natural number. But now we see that&nbsp;
when we make this shift to this data structure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:24.980 --> 00:28:31.580
point of view, regarding numbers as M-sets&nbsp;
of these more fundamental marks or strokes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:31.580 --> 00:28:39.080
then it’s natural to allow zero in the&nbsp;
picture, and so zero becomes a natural number.

00:28:39.080 --> 00:28:48.260
So, this is a shift that we're making, and I&nbsp;
don't apologize for it. I think we're open to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:48.260 --> 00:28:52.390
the possibility of changing our minds. It's&nbsp;
very important to have the ability and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:52.390 --> 00:28:57.760
willingness to change your mind. So, let's do&nbsp;
things a little bit differently from the way we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:57.760 --> 00:29:03.820
thought we were gonna do things before, right?&nbsp;
This is mathematics; it's not set in stone. We&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:03.820 --> 00:29:09.670
can proceed, erase something, change things,&nbsp;
reconsider, look at things a few years later,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:09.670 --> 00:29:12.670
and say, "Oh, actually, we should have&nbsp;
done this, this, and this." And we need&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:12.670 --> 00:29:18.250
to be prepared to then go back and actually do&nbsp;
things the better way—to rub out what we've got&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:18.250 --> 00:29:24.880
and to write in a new and better way. That, of&nbsp;
course, applies to a lot of modern mathematics.

00:29:24.880 --> 00:29:31.960
And, of course, the computer scientists can now&nbsp;
rejoice because now zero is part of the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:31.960 --> 00:29:39.190
number system, which computer scientists enjoy&nbsp;
because they like starting to count with zero. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:39.190 --> 00:29:45.580
this is very exciting. So, we've harnessed our&nbsp;
understanding of data structures for something&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:45.580 --> 00:29:56.170
very concrete and actually fundamental—namely,&nbsp;
we are pinning arithmetic onto the multiset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:56.170 --> 00:30:03.730
framework. We are creating natural numbers&nbsp;
from a relatively simple kind of ingredient,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:03.730 --> 00:30:11.620
and with this very important data structure&nbsp;
kind of thing in mind of a multiset.

00:30:11.620 --> 00:30:18.760
In our next video, we want to do something that's&nbsp;
even more fundamental. We want to go down right&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:24.850
to the bottom of the core of mathematics. So,&nbsp;
the natural numbers are pretty close to being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:24.850 --> 00:30:30.970
at the core of mathematics, but I claim that&nbsp;
there's really something underneath the natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:30.970 --> 00:30:34.450
numbers that’s sort of implicit in what we've&nbsp;
been talking about here, but I want to really&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:34.450 --> 00:30:41.200
identify what it is. So, there’s a fundamental&nbsp;
dichotomy in mathematics, a kind of a yin-yang,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:41.200 --> 00:30:47.080
which hasn’t properly been identified.&nbsp;
We need to put our fingers very clearly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:47.080 --> 00:30:54.280
on this and really identify this fundamental&nbsp;
dichotomy, which is at the core of mathematics,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:54.280 --> 00:31:03.660
and that we are going to use to build up our&nbsp;
arithmetic in, I think, a beautiful way. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:03.660 --> 00:31:09.510
in our next video, it's going to be a rather&nbsp;
important one in the sense that we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:09.510 --> 00:31:17.250
to really introduce an almost philosophically&nbsp;
novel way of thinking about what mathematics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:17.250 --> 00:31:24.150
ultimately is really about once we get right to&nbsp;
the bottom—what's the essence of mathematics?

00:31:24.150 --> 00:31:27.210
We're going to find out next&nbsp;
time. I hope you'll join me for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:27.210 --> 00:31:30.930
that. I'm Norman Wildberger. Thanks for listening.

